==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hem
<hw>Hem</hw> <pr>(h⟦ecr⟧m)</pr>, <pos>pron.</pos> <ety>[OE., fr. AS.
<ets>him</ets>, <ets>heom</ets>, dative pl. of. <ets>h⟦emac⟧</ets> he.
See <er>He</er>, <er>They</er>.]</ety> <def>Them</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hem</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hem
<hw>Hem</hw>, <pos>interj.</pos> <def>An onomatopoetic word used as an
expression of hesitation, doubt, etc. It is often a sort of voluntary
half cough, loud or subdued, and would perhaps be better expressed by
<xex>hm</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Cough or cry <qex>hem</qex>, if anybody come.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hem</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hem
<hw>Hem</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An utterance or sound of the voice,
<xex>hem</xex> or <xex>hm</xex>, often indicative of hesitation or
doubt, sometimes used to call attention.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧His morning
<xex>hems</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Spectator.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hem</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Hem
<hw>Hem</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[⟦root⟧15. See <er>Hem</er>,
<pos>interj.</pos>]</ety> <def>To make the sound expressed by the word
<xex>hem</xex>; hence, to hesitate in speaking.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Hem</xex>, and stroke thy beard.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hem</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Hem
<hw>Hem</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>hem</ets>, border, margin;
cf. Fries. <ets>h⟦aum⟧mel</ets>, Prov. G. <ets>hammel</ets> hem of mire
or dirt.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The edge or border of a garment or
cloth, doubled over and sewed, to strengthen it and prevent
raveling.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Border; edge; margin.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Hem</xex> of
the sea.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A border made on sheet-metal ware by doubling over
the edge of the sheet, to stiffen it and remove the sharp
edge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hem</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Hem
<hw>Hem</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Hemmed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Hemming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To form a hem or
border to; to fold and sew down the edge of.</def>
<rj><au>Wordsworth.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To border; to edge</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the skirt about⟦br⟧
Was <qex>hemmed</qex> with golden fringe.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To hem about</b></col>, <col><b>To hem
around</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>To hem in</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to
inclose and confine; to surround; to environ.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧With valiant
squadrons round <xex>about to hem</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Fairfax.</au>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Hemmed in</xex> to be a spoil to tyranny.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Daniel.</au> -- <col><b>To hem out</b></col>, <cd>to shut out.</cd>
⟦ldquo⟧You can not <xex>hem</xex> me <xex>out</xex> of London.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>J. Webster.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hema-</ent>⟦br⟧
